definition.value: A disaccharide derivative that consists of hesperetin substituted by a 6-O-(alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the gamma-carboxy group of glutamic acid with the amino group of Se-methylselenocysteine.
A dihydroxyflavanone compound having the two hydroxy substituents at the 4'- and 7-positions. Isolated from the root of Glycyrrhizae uralensis, it is a selective agonist for oestrogen receptor beta.
A 1-thio-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine compound having 1-S-hexadecyl- and 2-O-hexadecylphosphono substituents.
A trisaccharide composed of beta-D-glucopyranose, alpha-D-glucopyranose and beta-D-fructofuranose units.

A nitroglycerol that is glycerol in which the hydrogen atoms of all three hydroxy groups are replaced by nitro groups. It acts as a prodrug, releasing nitric oxide to open blood vessels and so alleviate heart pain.
The L-enantiomer of glucitol.
A primary amino compound that is the 5-hydroxy derivative of tryptamine.
A 1,5-dicarboxylic acid compound having a 3-amino substituent. It has been isolated from the extracts of the algae, Chondria armata.

A docosenoic acid having a cis- double bond at C-13. It is found particularly in brassicas - it is a major component of mustard and rapeseed oils and is produced by broccoli, Brussels sprouts, kale, and wallflowers.
A chromenone having the keto group located at the 2-position.
A toluate that is the conjugate base of m-toluic acid.
Polysaccharides composed of fructose residues.
An optically active form of alpha-aminobutyric acid having D-configuration.
An iodobenzoic acid with a single iodo substituent placed at the 2-position.
A polymer consisting of cis-linked prenyl units.
Quinoline substituted by hydroxy groups at the 4- and 6-positions. It is the product of 5-hydroxytryptophan metabolism, via monoamine oxidase catalysed conversion of 5-hydroxykynurenamine.
An octadecynoic acid having its triple bond at position 9.
Any hydroxyflavone in which is the ring hydrogen at position 3 of the heterocyclic ring is replaced by a hydroxy group.
A 2-aminopentanoic acid that has R-configuration.
A deoxyinosine phosphate that is 5'-inosinic acid in which the hydroxy group at position 2' by a hydrogen atom.
A deoxyinosine phosphate compound having a triphosphate group at the 5'-position.
The (1S,2S)-isomer of trans-1,2-dihydronaphthalene-1,2-diol.
A iridoid monoterpenoid glycoside isolated from Galium verum.
A member of the class of phosphonic acids that is phosphonic acid substituted by an aminomethyl group. It is a metabolite of the herbicide glyphosate.
A primary alcohol, being cinnamyl alcohol hydroxylated at C-4 and methoxylated at C-3 and -5.

A stilbenol that is trans-stilbene in which one of the phenyl groups is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 4, while the other phenyl group is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 5.
A linear polysaccharide in which the backbone consists of a variably sulfated repeating disaccharide unit.
A deoxypentose that is D-ribose in which the hydroxy group at position C-2 is replaced by hydrogen.
A straight-chain alkane with 12 carbon atoms. It has been isolated from the essential oils of various plants including Zingiber officinale (ginger).
A disaccharide derivative that is (S)-naringenin substituted by a 2-O-(alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
